        Guest Lecture · Tran Nhan Tong Institute · March 12, 2026
      </p>
      <h1 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; color: #faf5ee; font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.5rem); font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.3;">
        Science, Creation, Contingency, and the Human Person
      </h1>
      <p style="color: #a8a29e; font-size: 0.95rem; margin-top: 1rem; font-style: italic;">
        A Christian Conversation After Dependent Origination
      </p>
      <p style="color: #78716c; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.5rem;">
        prof. PhDr. Michal Valčo, PhD. · Evangelical Lutheran Theological Faculty, Comenius University
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== OPENING ========== -->
  <section id="opening" style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 3rem 1rem;">
    <div style="font-family: 'Lora', serif; color: #44403c; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.9;">
      <p style="font-family: sans-serif; color: #a85c32; font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.15em; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Opening</p>
      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">A Lutheran in a Buddhist Institute</h2>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Thank you very much for this kind invitation. It is a real pleasure to be here at the Tran Nhan Tong Institute in Hanoi, and an honor to speak in a setting where serious intellectual traditions are not treated as museum pieces, but as <strong>living ways of asking what reality is</strong>… and what kind of beings we are within it.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        And that matters. More than we sometimes admit.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        We live in an age that can build astonishing machines, predict behavior, edit genes, generate text, automate judgment — and still remain strangely unsure about what a human being is <em>for</em>. So when we gather to speak about philosophy of science, we are not really gathering only to discuss method. We are also asking… What kind of world makes knowledge possible? What kind of truth are we looking for? And what kind of person do we become while looking for it?
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        I should confess something. When I told my colleagues in Slovakia that I was flying to Hanoi to present a Christian philosophy of science at a Buddhist academic institute, there was a certain… silence. The kind of silence that usually means someone is trying to decide whether you need encouragement or an intervention. But here I am. And I am especially grateful to speak after a presentation on dependent origination as a Buddhist philosophy of science. That is a rich and serious theme. And, honestly, a helpful one — because it reminds us, right from the beginning, that things do not exist in splendid isolation. Reality is not a pile of self-enclosed atoms pretending not to need each other. That is not only bad philosophy. It is also, I suspect, bad manners.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The Oxford philosopher Alister McGrath has recently argued that we live in an age of <em>multiple situated rationalities</em> — that the Enlightenment dream of a single, universal, culturally invariant Reason has collapsed. What we actually find, across cultures and disciplines, is a plurality of domain-specific, historically embedded ways of reasoning, each genuine, each with its own integrity, none reducible to any other. The biologist Steven Rose put it with an elegant formula: we live in a world that is an <strong>ontological unity</strong>, but it demands an <strong>epistemological pluralism</strong>.
      </p>
        <aside class="margin-note">Steven Rose, <em>Lifelines</em> (1997). Rose is a neurobiologist; the formula bridges his critique of reductionism.</aside>
        
        <aside class="margin-note">McGrath, <em>Science &amp; Religion</em>, ch. 1 — on "multiple situated rationalities" and the end of Enlightenment foundationalism.</aside>
        

      <figure class="pull-quote--prose pull-quote--gold">
        The world is one. Our methods for knowing it are — and must be — many.
      </figure>

      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        That insight shapes everything I want to say today. If rationality were truly universal and singular, then a conversation between a Lutheran theologian and Buddhist philosophers could only be a contest — whose rationality wins? But if the world itself is too rich, too deep, too layered for any single method to exhaust, then our meeting here is not a competition. It is something like what the nineteenth-century philosopher William Whewell called <em>colligation</em> — the act of bringing together insights from genuinely different sources, the way a string holds together pearls of a necklace. Each pearl is real. The string does not destroy them. It reveals a pattern none of them could show alone.
      </p>
        <aside class="margin-note">William Whewell coined "colligation" in <em>Philosophy of the Inductive Sciences</em> (1840). <a href={`${base}glossary#colligation`} style="color:#c9a84c;">→ Glossary</a></aside>
        
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        I want to offer you a view from the other side of the same mountain. We may be climbing from different faces, and we may never fully agree on what is at the summit. But I suspect we see further when we occasionally call out to each other across the ridge.
      </p>

      <!-- Five Questions -->
      <InsightBox title="The Five Questions" color="teal">
<p style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>First:</strong> What kind of world makes science possible at all?</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Second:</strong> How does Christianity understand creation, order, and contingency?</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Third:</strong> Where do our traditions converge — and where do they honestly diverge?</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Fourth:</strong> Who is the knower — the scientist, the scholar, the person doing the knowing?</p>
          <p><strong>Fifth:</strong> Where do we find the limits of science — and what lies beyond them that is not irrational, but <em>trans-</em>rational?</p>
</InsightBox>

      <ScienceReligionTimeline client:visible />

